Intent Data: The Prospecting Superpower Most Teams Underuse
If you are not using intent data in your prospecting strategy in 2026, you are flying blind while your competitors use GPS.

Intent data tells you which companies are actively researching topics related to your product or service right now. This is not hypothetical interest. This is behavioral evidence collected from millions of content consumption signals across the web, including what articles they are reading, what whitepapers they are downloading, what keywords they are searching, and what competitor websites they are visiting.

First-Party vs. Third-Party Intent
First-party intent data comes from your own digital properties. It includes website visits, content downloads, webinar registrations, email engagement, and form fills. This data is high quality because it represents people who have already shown interest in your brand specifically.

Third-party intent data comes from external sources and content networks. It captures research behavior happening across the broader web, giving you visibility into accounts that are in-market even if they have never visited your website.

The most effective prospecting programs in 2026 combine both. When a target account appears in your third-party intent data and then visits your website, that is a high-priority signal. That account should be receiving outreach within hours, not weeks.

Content Syndication: Expanding Your Reach Into New Audiences
Content syndication remains one of the most cost-effective prospecting strategies available to B2B marketers in 2026. The idea is straightforward: distribute your high-value content, such as whitepapers, research reports, eBooks, and guides, across third-party platforms and publisher networks to generate leads from audiences that have never engaged with your brand directly.

What makes syndication powerful is the built-in qualification. When someone downloads a whitepaper titled "The Complete Guide to Cybersecurity Stack Optimization," they are telling you something important about where they are in the buying journey. That level of topic-specific intent is extremely valuable for sales teams.

Questions to Ask Before Running a Content Syndication Campaign
Is your content offering genuinely valuable, or is it thinly veiled marketing material?
Have you defined the audience filters, including job title, industry, company size, and geography, to ensure lead quality?
Do you have a follow-up sequence ready to nurture leads immediately after they download?
Are your landing pages and forms optimized for conversion on the syndication platform?
